title: A Phase IIa Safety and Tolerability Study to Investigate the Effect on Sleep of 3 Doses of AZD5213 and Placebo in Patients With Mild Alzheimer's Disease and Mild Cognitive Impairment During 4 Weeks of Treatment, Placebo-Controlled
description_brief: This is a study where AZD5213 or placebo is given to patients with Mild Alzheimer's Disease or Mild Cognitive Impairment in a blinded and random assignment. The main study objective is to estimate the relationship of sleep duration versus dose after 4 weeks of treatment.
description_detailed: A Phase IIa Safety and Tolerability Study to Investigate the Effect on Sleep of 3 Doses of AZD5213 and Placebo in Patients with Mild Alzheimer's Disease and Mild Cognitive Impairment During 4 Weeks of Treatment, Designed as a Randomized, Double-Blind, Multi-Center, Parallel Group, Placebo-Controlled Study

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: 164 subjects signed informed consent and 83 failed to qualify at the first screening visit for participation in the study.

measures.title: Mini-Mental State Examination
measures.description: Mini-Mental Scale Examination, Total Score range 0-30, higher score indicates less cognitive impairment

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Total Sleep Time (TST) After 4 Weeks of Treatment, Based on PSG Measurement.
outcomeMeasures.description: Total sleep time (TST) is defined as the total time in minutes, that subjects were determined to be in a sleep state by polysomnography (PSG) measurement.

adverseEventsModule.timeFrame: From first dose of study drug through the follow-up (up to 38 days total)

drug: AZD5213 (selective histamine H3 receptor antagonist/inverse agonist)
explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests AZD5213, which is described in the literature as a selective histamine H3 receptor antagonist/inverse agonist developed to affect wakefulness and cognition rather than to target Alzheimer pathology (amyloid or tau). H3 antagonists/inverse agonists are classically pursued as symptomatic cognitive/wakefulness enhancers. citeturn0search0turn0search4

Act: Key trial details — Phase IIa, randomized placebo-controlled study in mild AD/MCI assessing sleep (total sleep time) after 4 weeks of 3 AZD5213 doses vs placebo. The clinical-trial registry and publications identify AZD5213 as an H3 ligand with cognitive/wakefulness indications. citeturn0search1turn0search7

Reflect: Classification rationale — although this particular study's primary outcome is sleep (safety/tolerability impact on sleep), AZD5213's mechanism (H3 receptor inverse agonism/antagonism) is symptomatic and intended to modulate cognition and wakefulness rather than modify AD pathology. Under the provided category definitions this best fits 'cognitive enhancer' (category 3). Note ambiguity: because the trial focuses on sleep effects rather than direct cognitive endpoints, one might consider 'neuropsychiatric symptom improvement' if the intent were purely to treat sleep disturbance; however the drug class and development rationale align with cognitive enhancement/wakefulness modulation. citeturn0search0turn0search4

explanation_agent: Reason: AZD5213 is a selective histamine H3 receptor antagonist/inverse agonist — H3 is a neurotransmitter receptor involved in cognition and wake–sleep regulation, so the mechanism is modulation of a neurotransmitter receptor rather than targeting amyloid, tau, inflammation, or other AD pathologies. citeturn0search1turn0search2

Act: The trial is a Phase IIa randomized, placebo-controlled study (NCT01548287) in mild AD/MCI assessing sleep effects of three AZD5213 doses over 4 weeks; the registry and publications identify AZD5213 as an H3 ligand developed for cognitive/wakefulness indications. Based on that mechanism and trial intent, assign 'D) Neurotransmitter Receptors'. citeturn0search0turn0search3

Reflect: This classification aligns with CADRO because the drug targets a classical neurotransmitter receptor (histamine H3) and is intended for symptomatic modulation of cognition/wakefulness (and here sleep safety), not disease modification of core AD pathologies. The trial's sleep focus does not change the biological target class. citeturn0search1
